# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: reservoir-sampling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] In computer science, an **online algorithm** is one that can process its input piece-by-piece in a serial fashion, i.e., in the order that the input is fed to the algorithm, without having the entire input available from the start.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] In contrast, an **offline algorithm** is given the whole problem data from the beginning and is required to output an answer which solves the problem at hand.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] In operations research, the area in which online algorithms are developed is called online optimization.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] As an example, consider the sorting algorithms selection sort and insertion sort: selection sort repeatedly selects the minimum element from the unsorted remainder and places it at the front, which requires access to the entire input; it is thus an offline algorithm.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] On the other hand, insertion sort considers one input element per iteration and produces a partial solution without considering future elements.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] Thus insertion sort is an online algorithm.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] Note that the final result of an insertion sort is optimum, i.e., a correctly sorted list.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] For many problems, online algorithms cannot match the performance of offline algorithms.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] If the ratio between the performance of an online algorithm and an optimal offline algorithm is bounded, the online algorithm is called competitive.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] Not every *offline algorithm* has an efficient *online* counterpart.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] In grammar theory they are associated with Straight-line grammars.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] Because it does not know the whole input, an online algorithm is forced to make decisions that may later turn out not to be optimal, and the study of online algorithms has focused on the quality of decision-making that is possible in this setting.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] Competitive analysis formalizes this idea by comparing the relative performance of an online and offline algorithm for the same problem instance.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] Specifically, the competitive ratio of an algorithm, is defined as the worst-case ratio of its cost divided by the optimal cost, over all possible inputs.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] The competitive ratio of an online problem is the best competitive ratio achieved by an online algorithm.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] Intuitively, the competitive ratio of an algorithm gives a measure on the quality of solutions produced by this algorithm, while the competitive ratio of a problem shows the importance of knowing the future for this problem.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] A problem exemplifying the concepts of online algorithms is the Canadian traveller problem.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] The goal of this problem is to minimize the cost of reaching a target in a weighted graph where some of the edges are unreliable and may have been removed from the graph.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] However, that an edge has been removed (*failed*) is only revealed to *the traveller* when she/he reaches one of the edge's endpoints.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] The worst case for this problem is simply that all of the unreliable edges fail and the problem reduces to the usual shortest path problem.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] An alternative analysis of the problem can be made with the help of competitive analysis.
[src:reservoir-sampling/online-algorithm] For this method of analysis, the offline algorithm knows in advance which edges will fail and the goal is to minimize the ratio between the online and offline algorithms' performance.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Suppose we see a sequence of items, one at a time.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] We want to keep 10 items in memory, and we want them to be selected at random from the sequence.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] If we know the total number of items n and can access the items arbitrarily, then the solution is easy: select 10 distinct indices i between 1 and n with equal probability, and keep the i-th elements.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The problem is that we do not always know the exact n in advance.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] A simple and popular but slow algorithm, *Algorithm R*, was created by Jeffrey Vitter.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Initialize an array R indexed from 1 to k , containing the first k items of the input $x_{1},...,x_{k}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] For each new input $x_{i}$ , generate a random number j uniformly in $\{1,...,i\}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Return R after all inputs are processed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm works by induction on $i\geq k$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] When $i=k$ , Algorithm R returns all inputs, thus providing the basis for a proof by mathematical induction.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Apply Algorithm R to the $(i+1)$ -th input.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Input $x_{i+1}$ is included with probability ${\frac {k}{i+1}}$ by definition of the algorithm.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] For any other input $x_{r}\in \{x_{1},...,x_{i}\}$ , by the induction hypothesis, the probability that it is included in the reservoir just before the $(i+1)$ -th input is processed is ${\frac {k}{i}}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The probability that it is still included in the reservoir after $x_{i+1}$ is processed (in other words, that $x_{r}$ is not replaced by $x_{i+1}$ ) is ${\frac {k}{i}}\times \left(1-{\frac {1}{i+1}}\right)={\frac {k}{i+1}}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The latter follows from the assumption that the integer j is generated uniformly at random; once it becomes clear that a replacement will in fact occur, the probability that $x_{r}$ in particular is replaced by $x_{i+1}$ is ${\frac {k}{i+1}}{\frac {1}{k}}={\frac {1}{i+1}}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] We have shown that the probability that a new input enters the reservoir is equal to the probability that an existing input in the reservoir is retained.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Therefore, we conclude by the principle of mathematical induction that Algorithm R does indeed produce a uniform random sample of the inputs.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] While conceptually simple and easy to understand, this algorithm needs to generate a random number for each item of the input, including the items that are discarded.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The algorithm's asymptotic running time is thus $O(n)$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Generating this amount of randomness and the linear run time causes the algorithm to be unnecessarily slow if the input population is large.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] If we generate n random numbers $u_{1},...,u_{n}\sim U[0,1]$ independently, then the indices of the smallest k of them is a uniform sample of the k -subsets of $\{1,...,n\}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Now couple this with the stream of inputs $x_{1},...,x_{n}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Every time some $u_{i}$ is accepted, store the corresponding $x_{i}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Every time some $u_{i}$ is discarded, discard the corresponding $x_{i}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm still needs $O(n)$ random numbers, thus taking $O(n)$ time.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Second simplification: it's unnecessary to remember the entire array of the smallest k of $u_{1},...,u_{i}$ that has been seen so far, but merely w , the largest among them.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm computes three random numbers for each item that becomes part of the reservoir, and does not spend any time on items that do not.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Its expected running time is thus $O(k(1+\log(n/k)))$ , which is optimal.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] At the same time, it is simple to implement efficiently and does not depend on random deviates from exotic or hard-to-compute distributions.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] If we associate with each item of the input a uniformly generated random number, the k items with the largest (or, equivalently, smallest) associated values form a simple random sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] A simple reservoir-sampling thus maintains the k items with the currently largest associated values in a priority queue.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The expected running time of this algorithm is $O(n+k\log k\log(n/k))$ and it is relevant mainly because it can easily be extended to items with weights.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The methods presented in the previous sections do not allow to obtain a priori fixed inclusion probabilities.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Some applications require items' sampling probabilities to be according to weights associated with each item.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] For example, it might be required to sample queries in a search engine with weight as number of times they were performed so that the sample can be analyzed for overall impact on user experience.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Let the weight of item i be $w_{i}$ , and the sum of all weights be W.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The probability of each item to be included in the random sample is proportional to its relative weight, i.e., $w_{i}/W$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] It is not achievable when $k=n$ , since each item is then included with probability 1.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm is identical to the algorithm given in Reservoir Sampling with Random Sort except for the generation of the items' keys.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The algorithm is equivalent to assigning each item a key $r^{1/w_{i}}$ where r is the random number and then selecting the k items with the largest keys.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Equivalently, a more numerically stable formulation of this algorithm computes the keys as $-\ln(r)/w_{i}$ and select the k items with the *smallest* keys.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm follows the same mathematical properties that are used in A-Res, but instead of calculating the key for each item and checking whether that item should be inserted or not, it calculates an exponential jump to the next item which will be inserted.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] This avoids having to create random variates for each item, which may be expensive.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The number of random variates required is reduced from $O(n)$ to $O(k\log(n/k))$ in expectation, where k is the reservoir size, and n is the number of items in the stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Warning: the following description is wrong, see Chao's original paper and the discussion here.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Chao uses interpretation 2: and Tillé (2006).
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] For each item, its relative weight is calculated and used to randomly decide if the item will be added into the reservoir.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] If the item is selected, then one of the existing items of the reservoir is uniformly selected and replaced with the new item.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The trick here is that, if the probabilities of all items in the reservoir are already proportional to their weights, then by selecting uniformly which item to replace, the probabilities of all items remain proportional to their weight after the replacement.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Note that Chao doesn't specify how to sample the first *k* elements.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] He simple assumes we have some other way of picking them in proportion to their weight.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Chao: "Assume that we have a sampling plan of fixed size with respect to *S_k* at time *A*; such that its first-order inclusion probability of *X_t* is *π(k; i)*".
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Similar to the other algorithms, it is possible to compute a random weight `j` and subtract items' probability mass values, skipping them while `j > 0`, reducing the number of random numbers that have to be generated.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] In machine learning applications, fairness is a critical consideration, especially in scenarios where data streams exhibit class imbalance.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] To address this, Nikoloutsopoulos, Titsias, and Koutsopoulos proposed the Kullback-Leibler Reservoir Sampling (KLRS) algorithm as a solution to the challenges of Continual Learning, where models must learn incrementally from a continuous data stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The KLRS algorithm was designed to create a flexible policy that matches class percentages in the buffer to a target distribution while employing Reservoir Sampling techniques.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] This is achieved by minimizing the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence between the current buffer distribution and the desired target distribution.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] KLRS generalizes earlier methods like Reservoir Sampling and Class-Balancing Reservoir Sampling, as verified by experiments using confidence intervals, demonstrating its broader applicability and improved performance.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] The KLRS algorithm operates by maintaining a buffer of size and updating its contents as new data points arrive in a stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Suppose one wanted to draw k random cards from a deck of cards.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] A natural approach would be to shuffle the deck and then take the top k cards.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Note that although the rest of the cards are shuffled, only the first k are important in the present context.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Therefore, the array R need only track the cards in the first k positions while performing the shuffle, reducing the amount of memory needed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Since the order of the first k cards is immaterial, the first loop can be removed and R can be initialized to be the first k items of the input.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Reservoir sampling makes the assumption that the desired sample fits into main memory, often implying that k is a constant independent of n.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] In applications where we would like to select a large subset of the input list (say a third, i.e. $k=n/3$ ), other methods need to be adopted.
[src:reservoir-sampling/reservoir-sampling] Distributed implementations for this problem have been proposed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In statistics, quality assurance, and survey methodology, **sampling** is the selection of a subset of individuals from within a statistical population to estimate characteristics of the whole population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The subset, called a **statistical sample** (or **sample**, for short), is meant to reflect the whole population, and statisticians attempt to collect samples that are representative of the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sampling has lower costs and faster data collection compared to a census recording data from the entire population (in many cases, collecting the whole population is impossible, like getting sizes of all stars in the universe).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Thus, it can provide insights in cases where it is infeasible to measure an entire population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Each observation measures one or more properties (such as weight, location, colour or mass) of independent objects or individuals.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In survey sampling, weights can be applied to the data to adjust for the sample design, particularly in stratified sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Results from probability theory and statistical theory are employed to guide the practice.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In business and medical research, sampling is widely used for gathering information about a population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Acceptance sampling is used to determine if a production lot of material meets the governing specifications.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Random sampling by using lots is an old idea, mentioned several times in the Bible.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In 1786, Pierre Simon Laplace estimated the population of France by using a sample, along with ratio estimator.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] He also computed probabilistic estimates of the error.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] These were not expressed as modern confidence intervals but as the sample size that would be needed to achieve a particular upper bound on the sampling error with probability 1000/1001.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] His estimates used Bayes' theorem with a uniform prior probability and assumed that his sample was random.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Alexander Ivanovich Chuprov introduced sample surveys to Imperial Russia in the 1870s.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In the US, the 1936 *Literary Digest* prediction of a Republican win in the presidential election went badly awry, due to severe bias [1].
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] More than two million people responded to the study with their names obtained through magazine subscription lists and telephone directories.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It was not appreciated that these lists were heavily biased towards Republicans and the resulting sample, though very large, was deeply flawed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Successful statistical practice is based on focused problem definition.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In sampling, this includes defining the "population" from which our sample is drawn.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] A population can be defined as including all people or items with the characteristics one wishes to understand.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Because there is very rarely enough time or money to gather information from everyone or everything in a population, the goal becomes finding a representative sample (or subset) of that population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sometimes what defines a population is obvious.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, a manufacturer needs to decide whether a batch of material from production is of high enough quality to be released to the customer or should be scrapped or reworked due to poor quality.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In this case, the batch is the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Although the population of interest often consists of physical objects, sometimes it is necessary to sample over time, space, or some combination of these dimensions.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For instance, an investigation of supermarket staffing could examine checkout line length at various times, or a study on endangered penguins might aim to understand their usage of various hunting grounds over time.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For the time dimension, the focus may be on periods or discrete occasions.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In other cases, the examined 'population' may be even less tangible.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, Joseph Jagger studied the behaviour of roulette wheels at a casino in Monte Carlo, and used this to identify a biased wheel.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In this case, the 'population' Jagger wanted to investigate was the overall behaviour of the wheel (i.e. the probability distribution of its results over infinitely many trials), while his 'sample' was formed from observed results from that wheel.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Similar considerations arise when taking repeated measurements of properties of materials such as the electrical conductivity of copper.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This situation often arises when seeking knowledge about the cause system of which the *observed* population is an outcome.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In such cases, sampling theory may treat the observed population as a sample from a larger 'superpopulation'.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, a researcher might study the success rate of a new 'quit smoking' program on a test group of 100 patients, in order to predict the effects of the program if it were made available nationwide.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Here the superpopulation is "everybody in the country, given access to this treatment" – a group that does not yet exist since the program is not yet available to all.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The population from which the sample is drawn may not be the same as the population from which information is desired.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Often there is a large but not complete overlap between these two groups due to frame issues etc.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sometimes they may be entirely separate – for instance, one might study rats in order to get a better understanding of human health, or one might study records from people born in 2008 in order to make predictions about people born in 2009.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Time spent in making the sampled population and population of concern precise is often well spent because it raises many issues, ambiguities, and questions that would otherwise have been overlooked at this stage.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In the most straightforward case, such as the sampling of a batch of material from production (acceptance sampling by lots), it would be most desirable to identify and measure every single item in the population and to include any one of them in our sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] However, in the more general case this is not usually possible or practical.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] There is no way to identify all rats in the set of all rats.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Where voting is not compulsory, there is no way to identify which people will vote at a forthcoming election (in advance of the election).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] These imprecise populations are not amenable to sampling in any of the ways below and to which we could apply statistical theory.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] As a remedy, we seek a sampling frame which has the property that we can identify every single element and include any in our sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The most straightforward type of frame is a list of elements of the population (preferably the entire population) with appropriate contact information.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, in an opinion poll, possible sampling frames include an electoral register and a telephone directory.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] A **probability sample** is a sample in which every unit in the population has a chance (greater than zero) of being selected in the sample, and this probability can be accurately determined.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The combination of these traits makes it possible to produce unbiased estimates of population totals, by weighting sampled units according to their probability of selection.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In the above example, not everybody has the same probability of selection; what makes it a probability sample is the fact that each person's probability is known.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] When every element in the population *does* have the same probability of selection, this is known as an 'equal probability of selection' (EPS) design.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Such designs are also referred to as 'self-weighting' because all sampled units are given the same weight.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Probability sampling includes: simple random sampling, systematic sampling, stratified sampling, probability-proportional-to-size sampling, and cluster or multistage sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] 2. involves random selection at some point.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Nonprobability sampling methods include convenience sampling, quota sampling, snowball sampling, and purposive sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In addition, nonresponse effects may turn *any* probability design into a nonprobability design if the characteristics of nonresponse are not well understood, since nonresponse effectively modifies each element's probability of being sampled.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Within any of the types of frames identified above, a variety of sampling methods can be employed individually or in combination.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In a simple random sample (SRS) of a given size, all subsets of a sampling frame have an equal probability of being selected.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Each element of the frame thus has an equal probability of selection: the frame is not subdivided or partitioned.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Furthermore, any given *pair* of elements has the same chance of selection as any other such pair (and similarly for triples, and so on).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This minimizes bias and simplifies analysis of results.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In particular, the variance between individual results within the sample is a good indicator of variance in the overall population, which makes it relatively easy to estimate the accuracy of results.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Simple random sampling can be vulnerable to sampling error because the randomness of the selection may result in a sample that does not reflect the makeup of the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For instance, a simple random sample of ten people from a given country will *on average* produce five men and five women, but any given trial is likely to overrepresent one sex and underrepresent the other.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Systematic and stratified techniques attempt to overcome this problem by "using information about the population" to choose a more "representative" sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Also, simple random sampling can be cumbersome and tedious when sampling from a large target population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In some cases, investigators are interested in research questions specific to subgroups of the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, researchers might be interested in examining whether cognitive ability as a predictor of job performance is equally applicable across racial groups.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Simple random sampling cannot accommodate the needs of researchers in this situation, because it does not provide subsamples of the population, and other sampling strategies, such as stratified sampling, can be used instead.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling (also known as interval sampling) relies on arranging the study population according to some ordering scheme, and then selecting elements at regular intervals through that ordered list.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling involves a random start and then proceeds with the selection of every *k*th element from then onwards.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In this case, *k*=(population size/sample size).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It is important that the starting point is not automatically the first in the list, but is instead randomly chosen from within the first to the *k*th element in the list.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] A simple example would be to select every 10th name from the telephone directory (an 'every 10th' sample, also referred to as 'sampling with a skip of 10').
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] As long as the starting point is randomized, systematic sampling is a type of probability sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It is easy to implement and the stratification induced can make it efficient, *if* the variable by which the list is ordered is correlated with the variable of interest.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] 'Every 10th' sampling is especially useful for efficient sampling from databases.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, suppose we wish to sample people from a long street that starts in a poor area (house No.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] 1) and ends in an expensive district (house No.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] A simple random selection of addresses from this street could easily end up with too many from the high end and too few from the low end (or vice versa), leading to an unrepresentative sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Selecting (e.g.) every 10th street number along the street ensures that the sample is spread evenly along the length of the street, representing all of these districts.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] However, systematic sampling is especially vulnerable to periodicities in the list.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] If periodicity is present and the period is a multiple or factor of the interval used, the sample is especially likely to be *un*representative of the overall population, making the scheme less accurate than simple random sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, consider a street where the odd-numbered houses are all on the north (expensive) side of the road, and the even-numbered houses are all on the south (cheap) side.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Another drawback of systematic sampling is that even in scenarios where it is more accurate than SRS, its theoretical properties make it difficult to *quantify* that accuracy.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] As described above, systematic sampling is an EPS method, because all elements have the same probability of selection (in the example given, one in ten).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It is *not* 'simple random sampling' because different subsets of the same size have different selection probabilities – e.g., the set {4,14,24,...,994} has a one-in-ten probability of selection, but the set {4,13,24,34,...} has zero probability of selection.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling can also be adapted to a non-EPS approach; for an example, see discussion of PPS samples below.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] When the population embraces a number of distinct categories, the frame can be organized by these categories into separate "strata." Each stratum is then sampled as an independent sub-population, out of which individual elements can be randomly selected.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The ratio of the size of this random selection (or sample) to the size of the population is called a sampling fraction.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] There are several potential benefits to stratified sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] First, dividing the population into distinct, independent strata can enable researchers to draw inferences about specific subgroups that may be lost in a more generalized random sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Second, utilizing a stratified sampling method can lead to more efficient statistical estimates (provided that strata are selected based upon relevance to the criterion in question, instead of availability of the samples).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Even if a stratified sampling approach does not lead to increased statistical efficiency, such a tactic will not result in less efficiency than would simple random sampling, provided that each stratum is proportional to the group's size in the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Finally, since each stratum is treated as an independent population, different sampling approaches can be applied to different strata, potentially enabling researchers to use the approach best suited (or most cost-effective) for each identified subgroup within the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] There are, however, some potential drawbacks to using stratified sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] First, identifying strata and implementing such an approach can increase the cost and complexity of sample selection, as well as leading to increased complexity of population estimates.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Second, when examining multiple criteria, stratifying variables may be related to some, but not to others, further complicating the design, and potentially reducing the utility of the strata.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The variables upon which the population is stratified are strongly correlated with the desired dependent variable.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Allows use of different sampling techniques for different subpopulations.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Improves the accuracy/efficiency of estimation.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Permits greater balancing of statistical power of tests of differences between strata by sampling equal numbers from strata varying widely in size.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Is not useful when there are no homogeneous subgroups.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Stratification is sometimes introduced after the sampling phase in a process called "poststratification".
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This approach is typically implemented due to a lack of prior knowledge of an appropriate stratifying variable or when the experimenter lacks the necessary information to create a stratifying variable during the sampling phase.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Although the method is susceptible to the pitfalls of post hoc approaches, it can provide several benefits in the right situation.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Implementation usually follows a simple random sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In addition to allowing for stratification on an ancillary variable, poststratification can be used to implement weighting, which can improve the precision of a sample's estimates.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Choice-based sampling or oversampling is one of the stratified sampling strategies.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In choice-based sampling, the data are stratified on the target and a sample is taken from each stratum so that rarer target classes will be more represented in the sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The model is then built on this biased sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The effects of the input variables on the target are often estimated with more precision with the choice-based sample even when a smaller overall sample size is taken, compared to a random sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The results usually must be adjusted to correct for the oversampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In some cases the sample designer has access to an "auxiliary variable" or "size measure", believed to be correlated to the variable of interest, for each element in the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] These data can be used to improve accuracy in sample design.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] One option is to use the auxiliary variable as a basis for stratification, as discussed above.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Another option is probability proportional to size ('PPS') sampling, in which the selection probability for each element is set to be proportional to its size measure, up to a maximum of 1.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In a simple PPS design, these selection probabilities can then be used as the basis for Poisson sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] However, this has the drawback of variable sample size, and different portions of the population may still be over- or under-represented due to chance variation in selections.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling theory can be used to create a probability proportionate to size sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This is done by treating each count within the size variable as a single sampling unit.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Samples are then identified by selecting at even intervals among these counts within the size variable.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This method is sometimes called PPS-sequential or monetary unit sampling in the case of audits or forensic sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The PPS approach can improve accuracy for a given sample size by concentrating sample on large elements that have the greatest impact on population estimates.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] PPS sampling is commonly used for surveys of businesses, where element size varies greatly and auxiliary information is often available – for instance, a survey attempting to measure the number of guest-nights spent in hotels might use each hotel's number of rooms as an auxiliary variable.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In some cases, an older measurement of the variable of interest can be used as an auxiliary variable when attempting to produce more current estimates.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sometimes it is more cost-effective to select respondents in groups ('clusters').
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sampling is often clustered by geography or by time periods (nearly all samples are in some sense 'clustered' in time – although this is rarely taken into account in the analysis).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For instance, if surveying households within a city, we might choose to select 100 city blocks and then interview every household within the selected blocks.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Clustering can reduce travel and administrative costs.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In the example above, an interviewer can make a single trip to visit several households in one block, rather than having to drive to a different block for each household.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It also means that one does not need a sampling frame listing all elements in the target population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Instead, clusters can be chosen from a cluster-level frame, with an element-level frame created only for the selected clusters.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In the example above, the sample only requires a block-level city map for initial selections, and then a household-level map of the 100 selected blocks, rather than a household-level map of the whole city.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Cluster sampling (also known as clustered sampling) generally increases the variability of sample estimates above that of simple random sampling, depending on how the clusters differ between one another as compared to the within-cluster variation.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For this reason, cluster sampling requires a larger sample than SRS to achieve the same level of accuracy – but cost savings from clustering might still make this a cheaper option.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Cluster sampling is commonly implemented as multistage sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This is a complex form of cluster sampling in which two or more levels of units are embedded one in the other.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The first stage consists of constructing the clusters that will be used to sample from.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In the second stage, a sample of primary units is randomly selected from each cluster (rather than using all units contained in all selected clusters).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In following stages, in each of those selected clusters, additional samples of units are selected, and so on.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] All ultimate units (individuals, for instance) selected at the last step of this procedure are then surveyed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This technique, thus, is essentially the process of taking random subsamples of preceding random samples.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Multistage sampling can substantially reduce sampling costs, where the complete population list would need to be constructed (before other sampling methods could be applied).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] By eliminating the work involved in describing clusters that are not selected, multistage sampling can reduce the large costs associated with traditional cluster sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] However, each sample may not be a full representative of the whole population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In *quota sampling*, the population is first segmented into mutually exclusive sub-groups, just as in stratified sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Then judgement is used to select the subjects or units from each segment based on a specified proportion.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, an interviewer may be told to sample 200 females and 300 males between the age of 45 and 60.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It is this second step which makes the technique one of nonprobability sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In quota sampling the selection of the sample is non-random.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, interviewers might be tempted to interview those who look most helpful.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The problem is that these samples may be biased because not everyone gets a chance of selection.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This random element is its greatest weakness and quota versus probability has been a matter of controversy for several years.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In imbalanced datasets, where the sampling ratio does not follow the population statistics, one can resample the dataset in a conservative manner called minimax sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The minimax sampling has its origin in Anderson minimax ratio whose value is proved to be 0.5: in a binary classification, the class-sample sizes should be chosen equally.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This ratio can be proved to be minimax ratio only under the assumption of LDA classifier with Gaussian distributions.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The notion of minimax sampling is recently developed for a general class of classification rules, called class-wise smart classifiers.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In this case, the sampling ratio of classes is selected so that the worst case classifier error over all the possible population statistics for class prior probabilities, would be the best.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Accidental sampling (sometimes known as **grab**, **convenience**, or **opportunity sampling**) is a type of nonprobability sampling which involves the sample being drawn from that part of the population which is close to hand.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] That is, a population is selected because it is readily available and convenient.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It may be through meeting the person or including a person in the sample when one meets them or chosen by finding them through technological means such as the internet or through phone.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The researcher using such a sample cannot scientifically make generalizations about the total population from this sample because it would not be representative enough.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This type of sampling is most useful for pilot testing.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Is there good reason to believe that a particular convenience sample would or should respond or behave differently than a random sample from the same population?
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Is the question being asked by the research one that can adequately be answered using a convenience sample?
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In social science research, snowball sampling is a similar technique, where existing study subjects are used to recruit more subjects into the sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Some variants of snowball sampling, such as respondent driven sampling, allow calculation of selection probabilities and are probability sampling methods under certain conditions.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The voluntary sampling method is a type of nonprobability sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Volunteers may be invited through advertisements in social media.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The target population for advertisements can be selected by characteristics like location, age, sex, income, occupation, education, or interests using tools provided by the social medium.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The advertisement may include a message about the research and link to a survey.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] After following the link and completing the survey, the volunteer submits the data to be included in the sample population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This method can reach a global population but is limited by the campaign budget.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Volunteers outside the invited population may also be included in the sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It is difficult to make generalizations from this sample because it may not represent the total population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Often, volunteers have a strong interest in the main topic of the survey.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Line-intercept sampling is a method of sampling elements in a region whereby an element is sampled if a chosen line segment, called a "transect", intersects the element.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Snowball sampling involves finding a small group of initial respondents and using them to recruit more respondents.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It is particularly useful in cases where the population is hidden or difficult to enumerate.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Theoretical sampling occurs when samples are selected on the basis of the results of the data collected so far with a goal of developing a deeper understanding of the area or develop theories.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] An initial, general sample is first collected with the goal of investigating general trends, where further sampling may consist of extreme or very specific cases might be selected in order to maximize the likelihood a phenomenon will actually be observable.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In active sampling, the samples which are used for training a machine learning algorithm are actively selected, also compare active learning (machine learning).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Judgement sampling, also known as expert or purposive sampling, is a type of non-random sampling where samples are selected based on the opinion of an expert, who can select participants based on how valuable the information they provide is.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Haphazard sampling refers to the idea of using human judgement to simulate randomness.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Despite samples being hand-picked, the goal is to ensure that no conscious bias exists within the choice of samples, but often fails due to selection bias.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Haphazard sampling is generally opted for due to its convenience, when the tools or capacity to perform other sampling methods may not exist.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The major weakness of such samples is that they often do not represent the characteristics of the entire population, but just a segment of the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Because of this unbalanced representation, results from haphazard sampling are often biased.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sampling schemes may be *without replacement* ('WOR' – no element can be selected more than once in the same sample) or *with replacement* ('WR' – an element may appear multiple times in the one sample).
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, if we catch fish, measure them, and immediately return them to the water before continuing with the sample, this is a WR design, because we might end up catching and measuring the same fish more than once.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] However, if we do not return the fish to the water or tag and release each fish after catching it, this becomes a WOR design.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Formulas, tables, and power function charts are well known approaches to determine sample size.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Locate the column corresponding to the estimated effect size.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The intersection of the column and row is the minimum sample size required.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sampling enables the selection of right data points from within the larger data set to estimate the characteristics of the whole population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For example, there are about 600 million tweets produced every day.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] It is not necessary to look at all of them to determine the topics that are discussed during the day, nor is it necessary to look at all the tweets to determine the sentiment on each of the topics.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] A theoretical formulation for sampling Twitter data has been developed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In manufacturing different types of sensory data such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage, and controller data are available at short time intervals.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] To predict down-time it may not be necessary to look at all the data but a sample may be sufficient.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Survey results are typically subject to some error.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Total errors can be classified into sampling errors and non-sampling errors.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The term "error" here includes systematic biases as well as random errors.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Sampling errors and biases are induced by the sample design.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Random sampling error: Random variation in the results due to the elements in the sample being selected at random.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Non-sampling errors are other errors which can impact final survey estimates, caused by problems in data collection, processing, or sample design.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Under-coverage: sampling frame does not include elements in the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] After sampling, a review is held of the exact process followed in sampling, rather than that intended, in order to study any effects that any divergences might have on subsequent analysis.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] A particular problem involves *non-response*.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In survey sampling, many of the individuals identified as part of the sample may be unwilling to participate, not have the time to participate (opportunity cost), or survey administrators may not have been able to contact them.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In this case, there is a risk of differences between respondents and nonrespondents, leading to biased estimates of population parameters.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This is often addressed by improving survey design, offering incentives, and conducting follow-up studies which make a repeated attempt to contact the unresponsive and to characterize their similarities and differences with the rest of the frame.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The effects can also be mitigated by weighting the data (when population benchmarks are available) or by imputing data based on answers to other questions.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Nonresponse is particularly a problem in internet sampling.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Reasons for this problem may include improperly designed surveys, over-surveying (or survey fatigue), and the fact that potential participants may have multiple e-mail addresses, which they do not use anymore or do not check regularly.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] In many situations, the sample fraction may be varied by stratum and data will have to be weighted to correctly represent the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Thus for example, a simple random sample of individuals in the United Kingdom might not include some in remote Scottish islands who would be inordinately expensive to sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] A cheaper method would be to use a stratified sample with urban and rural strata.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] The rural sample could be under-represented in the sample, but weighted up appropriately in the analysis to compensate.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] More generally, data should usually be weighted if the sample design does not give each individual an equal chance of being selected.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] For instance, when households have equal selection probabilities but one person is interviewed from within each household, this gives people from large households a smaller chance of being interviewed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] This can be accounted for using survey weights.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Similarly, households with more than one telephone line have a greater chance of being selected in a random digit dialing sample, and weights can adjust for this.
[src:reservoir-sampling/sampling-statistics] Weights can also serve other purposes, such as helping to correct for non-response.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] In statistics, a **simple random sample** (or **SRS**) is a subset of individuals (a sample) chosen from a larger set (a population) in which a subset of individuals are chosen randomly, all with the same probability.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] It is a process of selecting a sample in a random way.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] In SRS, each subset of *k* individuals has the same probability of being chosen for the sample as any other subset of *k* individuals.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Simple random sampling is a basic type of sampling and can be a component of other more complex sampling methods.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] The principle of simple random sampling is that every set with the same number of items has the same probability of being chosen.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] For example, suppose 10 college students want a ticket for a basketball game, but there are only six tickets available to them, so they decide to have a fair way to see who gets to go.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Then, everybody is given a number in the range from 1 to 10, and random numbers are generated, either electronically or from a table of random numbers.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Numbers outside the range from 1 to 10 are ignored, as are any numbers previously selected.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] The first six numbers would identify the lucky ticket winners.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] In small populations and often in large ones, such sampling is typically done "**without replacement**", i.e., one deliberately avoids choosing any member of the population more than once.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Although simple random sampling can be conducted with replacement instead, this is less common and would normally be described more fully as simple random sampling **with replacement**.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Sampling done without replacement is no longer independent, but still satisfies exchangeability, hence most results of mathematical statistics still hold.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Further, for a small sample from a large population, sampling without replacement is approximately the same as sampling with replacement, since the probability of choosing the same individual twice is low.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Survey methodology textbooks generally consider simple random sampling without replacement as the benchmark to compute the relative efficiency of other sampling approaches.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] An unbiased random selection of individuals is important so that if many samples were drawn, the average sample would accurately represent the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] However, this does not guarantee that a particular sample is a perfect representation of the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Simple random sampling merely allows one to draw externally valid conclusions about the entire population based on the sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] The concept can be extended when the population is a geographic area.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] In this case, area sampling frames are relevant.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Conceptually, simple random sampling is the simplest of the probability sampling techniques.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] It requires a complete sampling frame, which may not be available or feasible to construct for large populations.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Even if a complete frame is available, more efficient approaches may be possible if other useful information is available about the units in the population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Advantages are that it is free of classification error, and it requires minimum previous knowledge of the population other than the frame.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Its simplicity also makes it relatively easy to interpret data collected in this manner.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] If these conditions do not hold, stratified sampling or cluster sampling may be a better choice.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] A sampling method for which each individual unit has the same chance of being selected is called **equal probability sampling** (epsem for short).
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Using a simple random sample will always lead to an epsem, but not all epsem samples are SRS.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] For example, if a teacher has a class arranged in 5 rows of 6 columns and she wants to take a random sample of 5 students she might pick one of the 6 columns at random.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] This would be an epsem sample but not all subsets of 5 pupils are equally likely here, as only the subsets that are arranged as a single column are eligible for selection.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] There are also ways of constructing multistage sampling, that are not srs, while the final sample will be epsem.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] For example, systematic random sampling produces a sample for which each individual unit has the same probability of inclusion, but different sets of units have different probabilities of being selected.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Samples that are epsem are **self weighting**, meaning that the inverse of selection probability for each sample is equal.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Consider a school with 1000 students, and suppose that a researcher wants to select 100 of them for further study.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] All their names might be put in a bucket and then 100 names might be pulled out.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] This means that every student in the school has in any case approximately a 1 in 10 chance of being selected using this method.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Further, any combination of 100 students has the same probability of selection.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] If a systematic pattern is introduced into random sampling, it is referred to as "systematic (random) sampling".
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] An example would be if the students in the school had numbers attached to their names ranging from 0001 to 1000, and we chose a random starting point, e.g.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] 0533, and then picked every 10th name thereafter to give us our sample of 100 (starting over with 0003 after reaching 0993).
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] In this sense, this technique is similar to cluster sampling, since the choice of the first unit will determine the remainder.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] This is no longer simple random sampling, because some combinations of 100 students have a larger selection probability than others – for instance, {3, 13, 23, ..., 993} has a 1/10 chance of selection, while {1, 2, 3, ..., 100} cannot be selected under this method.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] If the members of the population come in three kinds, say "blue", "red" and "black", the number of red elements in a sample of given size will vary by sample and hence is a random variable whose distribution can be studied.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] That distribution depends on the numbers of red and black elements in the full population.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] For a simple random sample *with* replacement, the distribution is a *binomial distribution*.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] For a simple random sample *without* replacement, one obtains a *hypergeometric distribution*.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Several efficient algorithms for simple random sampling have been developed.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] A naive algorithm is the draw-by-draw algorithm where at each step we remove the item at that step from the set with equal probability and put the item in the sample.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] We continue until we have a sample of desired size k .
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] The drawback of this method is that it requires random access in the set.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] The selection-rejection algorithm developed by Fan et al. in 1962 requires a single pass over data; however, it is a sequential algorithm and requires knowledge of total count of items n , which is not available in streaming scenarios.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] A very simple random sort algorithm was proved by Sunter in 1977.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] The algorithm simply assigns a random number drawn from uniform distribution $(0,1)$ as a key to each item, then sorts all items using the key and selects the smallest k items.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Vitter in 1985 proposed reservoir sampling algorithms, which are widely used.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] This algorithm does not require knowledge of the size of the population n in advance, and uses constant space.
[src:reservoir-sampling/simple-random-sample] Random sampling can also be accelerated by sampling from the distribution of gaps between samples and skipping over the gaps.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In computer science, **streaming algorithms** process input data streams as a sequence of items, typically making just one pass (or a few passes) through the data.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms are designed to operate with limited memory, generally logarithmic in the size of the stream and/or in the maximum value in the stream, and may also have limited processing time per item.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] As a result of these constraints, streaming algorithms often produce approximate answers based on a summary or "sketch" of the data stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Though streaming algorithms had already been studied by Munro and Paterson as early as 1978, as well as Philippe Flajolet and G.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Nigel Martin in 1982/83, the field of streaming algorithms was first formalized and popularized in a 1996 paper by Noga Alon, Yossi Matias, and Mario Szegedy.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Semi-streaming algorithms were introduced in 2005 as a relaxation of streaming algorithms for graphs, in which the space allowed is linear in the number of vertices *n*, but only logarithmic in the number of edges *m*.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] This relaxation is still meaningful for dense graphs, and can solve interesting problems (such as connectivity) that are insoluble in $o(n)$ space.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, some or all of the input is represented as a finite sequence of integers (from some finite domain) which is generally not available for random access, but instead arrives one at a time in a "stream".
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] If the stream has length *n* and the domain has size *m*, algorithms are generally constrained to use space that is logarithmic in *m* and *n*.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] They can generally make only some small constant number of passes over the stream, sometimes just one.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Much of the streaming literature is concerned with computing statistics on frequency distributions that are too large to be stored.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] For this class of problems, there is a vector $\mathbf {a} =(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ (initialized to the zero vector $\mathbf {0}$ ) that has updates presented to it in a stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The goal of these algorithms is to compute functions of $\mathbf {a}$ using considerably less space than it would take to represent $\mathbf {a}$ precisely.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] There are two common models for updating such streams, called the "cash register" and "turnstile" models.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In the cash register model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some positive integer c .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] A notable special case is when $c=1$ (only unit insertions are permitted).
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In the turnstile model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some (possibly negative) integer c .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In the "strict turnstile" model, no $a_{i}$ at any time may be less than zero.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Several papers also consider the "sliding window" model.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In this model, the function of interest is computing over a fixed-size window in the stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] As the stream progresses, items from the end of the window are removed from consideration while new items from the stream take their place.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Besides the above frequency-based problems, some other types of problems have also been studied.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Many graph problems are solved in the setting where the adjacency matrix or the adjacency list of the graph is streamed in some unknown order.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] There are also some problems that are very dependent on the order of the stream (i.e., asymmetric functions), such as counting the number of inversions in a stream and finding the longest increasing subsequence.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms have many similarities with online algorithms since they both require decisions to be made before all data are available, but they are not identical.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Data stream algorithms only have limited memory available but they may be able to defer action until a group of points arrive, while online algorithms are required to take action as soon as each point arrives.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] If the algorithm is an approximation algorithm then the accuracy of the answer is another key factor.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The accuracy is often stated as an $(\epsilon ,\delta )$ approximation meaning that the algorithm achieves an error of less than $\epsilon$ with probability $1-\delta$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Streaming algorithms have several applications in networking such as monitoring network links for elephant flows, counting the number of distinct flows, estimating the distribution of flow sizes, and so on.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] They also have applications in databases, such as estimating the size of a join .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The kth frequency moment of a set of frequencies $\mathbf {a}$ is defined as $F_{k}(\mathbf {a} )=\sum _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{k}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The first moment $F_{1}$ is simply the sum of the frequencies (i.e., the total count).
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The second moment $F_{2}$ is useful for computing statistical properties of the data, such as the Gini coefficient of variation. $F_{\infty }$ is defined as the frequency of the most frequent items.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The seminal paper of Alon, Matias, and Szegedy dealt with the problem of estimating the frequency moments.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] A direct approach to find the frequency moments requires to maintain a register mi for all distinct elements *a**i* ∈ (1,2,3,4,...,*N*) which requires at least memory of order $\Omega (N)$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] But we have space limitations and require an algorithm that computes in much lower memory.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] This can be achieved by using approximations instead of exact values.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] An algorithm that computes an (*ε,δ*)approximation of Fk, where F'k is the (*ε,δ*)- approximated value of Fk.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Where *ε* is the approximation parameter and *δ* is the confidence parameter.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in introduced a probabilistic method of counting which was inspired from a paper by Robert Morris.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Morris in his paper says that if the requirement of accuracy is dropped, a counter *n* can be replaced by a counter log *n* which can be stored in log log *n* bits.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in improved this method by using a hash function h which is assumed to uniformly distribute the element in the hash space (a binary string of length L).
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Let $\rho (y)$ represents the position of least significant 1-bit in the binary representation of yi with a suitable convention for $\rho (0)$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Let *A* be the sequence of data stream of length *M* whose cardinality need to be determined.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] hash space where the ρ(*hashedvalues*) are recorded.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The below algorithm then determines approximate cardinality of *A*.
