[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm describes the first attempt to approximate *F*0 in the data stream by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Their algorithm picks a random hash function which they assume to uniformly distribute the hash values in hash space.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Bar-Yossef et al. in introduced k-minimum value algorithm for determining number of distinct elements in data stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] They used a similar hash function *h* which can be normalized to [0,1] as $h:[m]\rightarrow [0,1]$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] But they fixed a limit *t* to number of values in hash space.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The value of *t* is assumed of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ (i.e. less approximation-value *ε* requires more *t*).
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm keeps only *t*-smallest hash values in the hash space.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] After all the *m* values of stream have arrived, $\upsilon =\mathrm {Max} (h(a_{i}))$ is used to calculate $F'_{0}={\dfrac {t}{\upsilon }}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] That is, in a close-to uniform hash space, they expect at-least *t* elements to be less than $O\left({\dfrac {t}{F_{0}}}\right)$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm can be implemented in $O\left(\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ memory bits space.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Each hash value requires space of order $O(\log(m))$ memory bits.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] There are hash values of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The access time can be reduced if we store the *t* hash values in a binary tree.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Thus the time complexity will be reduced to $O\left(\log \left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon }}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. estimates Fk by defining random variables that can be computed within given space and time.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The expected value of random variables gives the approximate value of Fk.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Assume length of sequence *m* is known in advance.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Algorithm takes *S*2 random variable $Y_{1},Y_{2},...,Y_{S2}$ and outputs the median Y .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Where Yi is the average of Xij where 1 ≤ *j* ≤ *S*1.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Now calculate expectation of random variable *E*(*X*).
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] From the algorithm to calculate Fk discussed above, we can see that each random variable X stores value of ap and r.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] So, to compute X we need to maintain only log(*n*) bits for storing ap and log(*n*) bits for storing r.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Total number of random variable X will be the ⁠ $S_{1}*S_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm calculates $F_{2}$ in order of $O({\sqrt {n}}(\log m+\log n))$ memory bits.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. in simplified this algorithm using four-wise independent random variable with values mapped to $\{-1,1\}$ .
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, the **frequent elements problem** is to output a set of elements that constitute more than some fixed fraction of the stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] A special case is the **majority problem**, which is to determine whether or not any value constitutes a majority of the stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] More formally, fix some positive constant *c* > 1, let the length of the stream be *m*, and let *f**i* denote the frequency of value *i* in the stream.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The frequent elements problem is to output the set { *i* | *f**i* > m/c }.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Detecting events in data streams is often done using a heavy hitters algorithm as listed above: the most frequent items and their frequency are determined using one of these algorithms, then the largest increase over the previous time point is reported as trend.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] This approach can be refined by using exponentially weighted moving averages and variance for normalization.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Counting the number of distinct elements in a stream (sometimes called the *F*0 moment) is another problem that has been well studied.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] The first algorithm for it was proposed by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] In 2010, Daniel Kane, Jelani Nelson and David Woodruff found an asymptotically optimal algorithm for this problem.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] It uses *O*(*ε*2 + log *d*) space, with *O*(1) worst-case update and reporting times, as well as universal hash functions and a r-wise independent hash family where *r* = Ω(log(1/*ε*) / log log(1/*ε*)).
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Learn a model (e.g. a classifier) by a single pass over a training set.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] Lower bounds have been computed for many of the data streaming problems that have been studied.
[src:reservoir-sampling/streaming-algorithm] By far, the most common technique for computing these lower bounds has been using communication complexity.
